e ranges (inclusive) of consecutive floors without a special floor:\n- (2, 3) with a total amount of 2 floors.\n- (5, 5) with a total amount of 1 floor.\n- (7, 9) with a total amount of 3 floors.\nTherefore, we return the maximum number which is 3 floors.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: bottom = 6, top = 8, special = [7,6,8]\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: Every floor rented is a special floor, so we return 0.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= special.length <= 105\n1 <= bottom <= special[i] <= top <= 109\nAll the values of special are unique.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maxConsecutive(self, bottom: int, top: int, special: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def maxConsecutive(self, bottom: int, top: int, special: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Sort the special floors\n        special.sort()\n        \n        # Initialize the maximum consecutive floors without a special floor\n        max_consecutive = 0\n        \n        # Check the number of consecutive floors before the first special floor\n        max_consecutive = max(max_consecutive, special[0] - bottom)\n        \n        # Check the number of consecutive floors between special floors\n        for i in range(1, len(special)):\n            max_consecutive = max(max_consecutive, special[i] - special[i - 1] - 1)\n        \n        # Check the number of consecutive floors after the last special floor\n        max_consecutive = max(max_consecutive, top - special[-1])\n        \n        return max_consecutive\n```\n\nThis solution first sorts the list of special floors. It then calculates the maximum number of consecutive non-special floors by checking the gaps between the sorted special floors, as well as the gaps from the `bottom` to the first special floor and from the last special floor to the `top`. The result is the maximum of these values.", "estimated_date": 1652572800000}